So

25
00:01:23.780 --> 00:01:26.660
really why I think we're all here in this

26
00:01:27.700 --> 00:01:31.420
room is to try to... We know cancer is a

27
00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:34.440
genetic-driven disease, and it undergoes

28
00:01:34.500 --> 00:01:37.890
evolution in the absence of therapy, as well as

29
00:01:37.940 --> 00:01:41.320
accelerated evolution in the presence of therapy.

30
00:01:41.340 --> 00:01:44.560
And so when random mutations land on

31
00:01:44.600 --> 00:01:48.340
proto-oncogenes, like KRAS, such as the glycine

32
00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:52.040
12 mutation, it drives a signaling pathway that lets the

33
00:01:52.100 --> 00:01:55.120
cell grow in the absence of external growth factors.

34
00:01:55.820 --> 00:01:59.780
Luckily, that single point mutation is not enough to create the tumor

35
00:01:59.820 --> 00:02:01.320
because of the

36
00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:04.760
oncogene-induced stress

37
00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:08.880
triggers tumor suppressor functions like p53, the

38
00:02:08.920 --> 00:02:12.660
transcription factor that transcribes a whole program, a whole

39
00:02:12.800 --> 00:02:16.740
set of genes to block the cell cycle or push the

40
00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:20.600
cell into apoptosis. But that cell is not

41
00:02:20.660 --> 00:02:24.640
growing, but it is in a senescent state, and it is itself subject

42
00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:28.280
to further mutational attack. And when p53, for example,

43
00:02:28.360 --> 00:02:32.160
gets mutated, the brakes come off and the cell is rapidly

44
00:02:32.280 --> 00:02:35.720
undergoing the cell cycle. That rapid

45
00:02:36.200 --> 00:02:40.000
cell division in the absence of normal checkpoints leads to

46
00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:43.740
accumulation of more and more mutations, and these mutations can

47
00:02:43.780 --> 00:02:47.600
be other driver mutations, or they can be just simple passenger

48
00:02:47.640 --> 00:02:51.540
mutations. But once these accumulate enough, then, of course, this

49
00:02:51.560 --> 00:02:55.200
cell looks more and more foreign to the immune system.

50
00:02:55.920 --> 00:02:59.360
And through presentation by class I

51
00:02:59.420 --> 00:03:03.340
MHC of neoantigenic peptides, these

52
00:03:03.350 --> 00:03:07.260
complexes can be recognized by T cells that have T cell

53
00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:09.600
receptors to these foreign peptides.

54
00:03:09.640 --> 00:03:13.470
They're not foreign from a virus, of course, but they're foreign in the sense that

55
00:03:13.480 --> 00:03:15.540
they're not genomically encoded.

56
00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:19.700
So they are this product of somatic mutation inside that tumor

57
00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:23.680
cell. If that recognition happens, the tumor could be eliminated.

58
00:03:24.120 --> 00:03:27.680
But of course, we know that the tumor cell can fight back on the immune

59
00:03:27.760 --> 00:03:31.600
system, upregulating PD-L1 to try to

60
00:03:31.640 --> 00:03:35.540
trigger PD-1, the suppressor, to silence the

61
00:03:35.580 --> 00:03:39.290
T cell, and thereby prevent the immune system from

62
00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:43.200
killing the tumor cell. But luckily, the breakthroughs of immune

63
00:03:43.240 --> 00:03:46.640
oncology and the checkpoint therapies, like

64
00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:50.829
anti-PD-1 or anti-PD-L1, allows us to take those breaks

65
00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:53.980
off and then let the T cell kill the tumor cell.

66
00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:56.660
So this is a

67
00:03:57.500 --> 00:03:59.940
picture of, I think, where we are right now.

68
00:03:59.980 --> 00:04:03.740
We have many inhibitors of the oncogenes, over 100

69
00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:07.730
kinase inhibitors, new KRAS inhibitors that I'll mention a little bit

70
00:04:07.820 --> 00:04:10.300
of, but we'll hear a lot more of at the meeting.

71
00:04:10.920 --> 00:04:13.420
We know tumor suppressor loss is a big driver.

72
00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:17.380
We don't have the best ways to exploit that, except in the case of PARP

73
00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:21.221
inhibitors with BRCA mutations and maybe PRMT5

74
00:04:21.231 --> 00:04:25.060
inhibitors in CDKN2A loss. And a

75
00:04:25.120 --> 00:04:28.800
few bespoke examples. That's a big opportunity, I think,

76
00:04:29.100 --> 00:04:31.980
that would really help us prevent the emergence of resistance.

77
00:04:33.220 --> 00:04:37.080
The point I'd like to make in my talk is that if we can

78
00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:40.700
pick the right kinds of inhibitors of the oncogenes

79
00:04:42.640 --> 00:04:46.400
in the oncogene group and pair that with the right

80
00:04:46.560 --> 00:04:50.300
IO therapies, then we might be able to get more durable

81
00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:55.500
and complete responses. And I'll try to walk through two examples that have

82
00:04:55.560 --> 00:04:59.340
emerged in the literature recently on how to do that, which I think are very

83
00:04:59.360 --> 00:05:00.780
exciting and I'd like to highlight.

84
00:05:01.760 --> 00:05:01.920
So

85
00:05:03.060 --> 00:05:06.860
I know Chiara and I will talk about KRAS, so I want to make sure

86
00:05:06.920 --> 00:05:10.400
that you're all familiar with the RAS cycle.

87
00:05:11.460 --> 00:05:15.380
So GTPases bind to GDP and GTP.

88
00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:17.430
In the GDP state, they are off.

89
00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:22.060
They have two elements, the switch loops here,

90
00:05:22.220 --> 00:05:25.920
switch one and switch two, that are essentially disordered

91
00:05:26.060 --> 00:05:30.020
and in the wrong conformation to stimulate or recruit downstream

92
00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:32.500
effectors like PI3 kinase or BRAF.

93
00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:37.000
But in the GTP state, those switch peptides are

94
00:05:37.060 --> 00:05:41.020
folded and are in the state competent for binding PI3 kinase and

95
00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:44.540
BRAF and turning on the signal. In order to proceed from the

96
00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:48.240
GDP off state to the GTP state, we need a guanine

97
00:05:48.260 --> 00:05:51.912
exchange factor to strip out the nucleotideThe

98
00:05:51.972 --> 00:05:55.862
cell then has higher GTP concentration and loads GTP.

99
00:05:55.972 --> 00:05:59.622
Then the timer on the GTPase is set, and it has two

100
00:05:59.622 --> 00:06:03.012
ways to wind down to the GDP state through a

101
00:06:03.092 --> 00:06:06.902
slow intrinsic hydrolysis or a rapid GTPase

102
00:06:06.992 --> 00:06:10.172
activating protein, a rapid GAP catalyzed hydrolysis.

103
00:06:10.572 --> 00:06:13.972
That turns out to be the key feature that the

104
00:06:14.012 --> 00:06:16.412
mutations at the glycine 12 exploit.

105
00:06:16.772 --> 00:06:20.552
These glycine 12 mutations early on were confusing to people because it

106
00:06:20.632 --> 00:06:22.312
seemed like such a subtle mutation.

107
00:06:22.412 --> 00:06:26.332
Why would a subtle mutation like a glycine have such a big impact on

108
00:06:26.372 --> 00:06:30.252
a protein? The answer turned out to be discovered from

109
00:06:30.472 --> 00:06:33.912
my colleague Frank McCormick, who identified that these glycine 12

110
00:06:33.932 --> 00:06:37.712
mutations work in trans. They disrupt the

111
00:06:37.752 --> 00:06:40.072
gap from stimulating hydrolysis.

112
00:06:41.172 --> 00:06:42.892
Then Fred Vettinghoffer

113
00:06:43.872 --> 00:06:47.752
in Dortmund had realized and solved the co-crystal structure of the

114
00:06:47.832 --> 00:06:51.532
GAP RAS complex, and here you can see the glycine 12

115
00:06:51.592 --> 00:06:54.632
mutation is exactly at the interface pointing at a

116
00:06:54.692 --> 00:06:58.132
catalytically key residue from the gap that accelerates

117
00:06:58.172 --> 00:06:59.152
hydrolysis. So

118
00:07:00.112 --> 00:07:03.602
any residue other than glycine will push the arginine away,

119
00:07:03.732 --> 00:07:07.672
diminishing the gap, and then letting the protein stay in

120
00:07:07.712 --> 00:07:10.932
the GTP state for a much longer time.

121
00:07:10.952 --> 00:07:14.692
And so this turns out to be a fascinating

122
00:07:14.772 --> 00:07:18.212
mutation because there are different spectra of

123
00:07:18.272 --> 00:07:21.812
mutations of alleles that emerge in the different RAS-driven

124
00:07:21.892 --> 00:07:25.432
cancers. These are the 12 most lethal cancers in the US.

125
00:07:25.632 --> 00:07:28.542
In green is incidence, in yellow is mortality.

126
00:07:29.232 --> 00:07:32.992
In blue are the fraction of those patients that have a RAS mutation.

127
00:07:33.672 --> 00:07:37.632
So it's about 30% of lung, about half of colon, almost

128
00:07:37.832 --> 00:07:41.792
90% plus of pancreatic cancer being the prototypical KRAS

129
00:07:41.832 --> 00:07:42.572
driven disease.

130
00:07:43.792 --> 00:07:47.632
As I said, there's a different spectrum of mutations in each of these

131
00:07:48.492 --> 00:07:52.362
diseases. Pancreas, it's dominated by aspartate, then valine, then

132
00:07:52.392 --> 00:07:56.172
cysteine. Colon, it's half aspartate, cysteine

133
00:07:56.232 --> 00:08:00.172
grows in a bit. In the smoking-induced cancer, cysteine in lung

134
00:08:00.192 --> 00:08:01.232
becomes the dominant.

135
00:08:02.052 --> 00:08:05.972
And when you look at the fraction of all of these together, you see

136
00:08:06.072 --> 00:08:09.672
again, aspartate is dominant, valine, and then cysteine.

137
00:08:10.412 --> 00:08:10.572
So

138
00:08:11.452 --> 00:08:11.812
it's

139
00:08:13.112 --> 00:08:16.652
possible, and we know that in many cases, a patient might

140
00:08:16.692 --> 00:08:19.872
present late stage with several of these alleles.

141
00:08:20.332 --> 00:08:23.432
And so there might already be preexisting resistance.

142
00:08:23.972 --> 00:08:27.872
Now, what we're very fortunate to have, I think, are

143
00:08:27.952 --> 00:08:31.112
exquisitely selective inhibitors of KRAS.

144
00:08:31.292 --> 00:08:35.153
These were developed in our lab to target

145
00:08:35.212 --> 00:08:38.413
the cysteine because it's the most attractive chemically.

146
00:08:38.512 --> 00:08:42.112
We can make a covalent bond, an irreversible bond to that

147
00:08:42.153 --> 00:08:45.022
cysteine. It's not the most frequent mutation.

148
00:08:45.872 --> 00:08:49.452
You see it's the third most frequent, but it gives us that chemical

149
00:08:49.492 --> 00:08:52.092
handle to trap the drug onto the complex.

150
00:08:52.512 --> 00:08:56.372
The other feature that I want to stress in this talk is that if it's

151
00:08:56.381 --> 00:09:00.282
selective for cysteine, it does not bind to wild type or any of the other

152
00:09:00.312 --> 00:09:04.142
alleles. So we have an allele-specific inhibitor that should have

153
00:09:04.192 --> 00:09:07.852
a very high therapeutic index because it doesn't target the wild type RAS.

154
00:09:08.332 --> 00:09:11.952
That'll be important in a moment in the immune side of

155
00:09:12.032 --> 00:09:15.972
things. So when we targeted cysteine, we identified a drug that

156
00:09:16.092 --> 00:09:18.532
bound to that cysteine. Here's the cysteine 12.

157
00:09:18.892 --> 00:09:22.782
Here's the nucleotide pocket. Here's the early form of the drug, and

158
00:09:22.852 --> 00:09:26.812
it found a pocket in the protein under the switch two loop,

159
00:09:27.152 --> 00:09:30.922
and that is what we call this pocket, the switch two pocket binders.

160
00:09:31.482 --> 00:09:34.922
And this then served as a starting point to optimize the molecule.

161
00:09:35.532 --> 00:09:39.292
So we reported that in 2013. We converted it into a

162
00:09:39.332 --> 00:09:42.492
cell-active molecule. Our colleagues at Auraxis then

163
00:09:42.552 --> 00:09:46.292
elaborated the molecule more and more to be more specific

164
00:09:46.352 --> 00:09:50.221
until this molecule, reported in 2018, was

165
00:09:50.312 --> 00:09:51.132
able to inhibit

166
00:09:51.992 --> 00:09:55.572
tumor growth in animals. And then a number of other

167
00:09:55.672 --> 00:09:59.032
groups have really elaborated the scaffold and made

168
00:09:59.632 --> 00:10:03.562
active clinical agents until the first two agents, sotorasib

169
00:10:03.592 --> 00:10:06.912
and adagrasib, were approved in 2020 and 2021.

170
00:10:07.912 --> 00:10:11.832
So now we have a number of these agents, and to give you an

171
00:10:11.872 --> 00:10:15.652
idea of what the clinical responses look like, this is the

172
00:10:15.712 --> 00:10:16.072
next

173
00:10:17.272 --> 00:10:20.972
farthest along molecule that is the so-called G12C off

174
00:10:21.032 --> 00:10:24.552
inhibitor, so it binds to cysteine very selectively.

175
00:10:25.592 --> 00:10:29.572
And in the off state, which I won't get into in this talk, but you can

176
00:10:29.632 --> 00:10:33.212
see about 80% disease control. You can see a single

177
00:10:33.232 --> 00:10:36.732
example of a complete response in this waterfall plot, but

178
00:10:36.772 --> 00:10:40.632
then you notice a patient responded, but then had

179
00:10:40.652 --> 00:10:42.232
progressive disease and relapsed.

180
00:10:42.272 --> 00:10:46.092
And that's kind of the summary slide for why we're all here in this session

181
00:10:46.172 --> 00:10:50.132
today, is to really prioritize these kinds

182
00:10:50.172 --> 00:10:53.792
of patients. How can we get better therapies to them

183
00:10:53.912 --> 00:10:57.372
earlier so that their responses become

184
00:10:57.432 --> 00:10:58.732
permanent and more durable?

185
00:10:59.852 --> 00:11:00.472
So

186
00:11:01.452 --> 00:11:05.232
this is sort of where the field is now, and I'd like

187
00:11:05.292 --> 00:11:08.772
to now start to introduce the immune oncology

188
00:11:08.852 --> 00:11:12.392
side of therapies and try to...

189
00:11:12.862 --> 00:11:15.392
Oh, I'm very sorry. Try to put those two together.

190
00:11:15.532 --> 00:11:19.492
So this is the now classic cancer immunity cycle from Ira

191
00:11:19.532 --> 00:11:23.332
Mellman's group at Genentech, where we have a tumor, and

192
00:11:23.352 --> 00:11:27.012
when cells are killed or die naturally in that tumor,

193
00:11:27.832 --> 00:11:31.412
they release these neoantigens. Again, these are those peptides that have the

194
00:11:31.452 --> 00:11:34.392
mutations that are the somatic mutants in the tumor cell.

195
00:11:34.922 --> 00:11:38.912
Antigen-presenting cells capture those, present those, carry them to

196
00:11:38.972 --> 00:11:42.872
lymph nodes, stimulate T cells, educate the T cells so

197
00:11:42.932 --> 00:11:46.852
that these CTLs can then traffic, hone

198
00:11:46.912 --> 00:11:50.822
back to the tumor, and then make an immunological synapse back on the

199
00:11:50.912 --> 00:11:54.628
tumor cell and kill them.So now that we've

200
00:11:54.948 --> 00:11:58.628
got these KRAS inhibitors and patients are on them,

201
00:11:59.168 --> 00:12:03.108
what kinds of effects are we seeing, and what can

202
00:12:03.178 --> 00:12:07.068
we leverage from that knowledge? So the point here is

203
00:12:07.128 --> 00:12:11.038
that we've got a tumor. It has a G12C driver mutation.

204
00:12:11.068 --> 00:12:12.868
We have a selective inhibitor for it.

205
00:12:13.258 --> 00:12:17.128
It has passenger mutations as well, and the immune system can see all

206
00:12:17.188 --> 00:12:19.988
of that, or it can see a subset of that.

207
00:12:20.028 --> 00:12:22.228
It's capable of seeing all of that.

208
00:12:22.308 --> 00:12:25.708
And what's, I think, very attractive about these allele-specific

209
00:12:25.728 --> 00:12:29.408
inhibitors, different than many of the targeted therapies in the kinase

210
00:12:29.448 --> 00:12:33.208
class that we've had, is that when we think about the immunological

211
00:12:33.348 --> 00:12:37.148
synapse, we know that these molecules are

212
00:12:37.228 --> 00:12:39.188
only selective for the tumor cells.

213
00:12:39.248 --> 00:12:43.128
So they spare the T cell and may let the T cell do more

214
00:12:43.168 --> 00:12:46.948
effective killing because we're not inhibiting the T cell's function.

215
00:12:47.708 --> 00:12:51.688
So that's, I think, the promise of it, but getting that to play

216
00:12:51.748 --> 00:12:54.188
out correctly, of course, is a big challenge.

217
00:12:54.708 --> 00:12:54.828
So,

218
00:12:57.028 --> 00:13:00.968
to remind you what immune checkpoint therapy does

219
00:13:01.088 --> 00:13:04.758
on its own and what it requires for the most best responses,

220
00:13:05.278 --> 00:13:09.128
we need many neoantigens. So we need high

221
00:13:09.168 --> 00:13:12.498
tumor mutation burden in order to get the best responses.

222
00:13:12.978 --> 00:13:16.248
And so the earliest responses to checkpoint

223
00:13:16.288 --> 00:13:20.148
therapies were in the far right here, where we

224
00:13:20.188 --> 00:13:22.508
have the highest number of mutations.

225
00:13:22.548 --> 00:13:24.008
These are hundreds to thousands

226
00:13:25.008 --> 00:13:28.958
of mutations per megabase of DNA. So these are chock-full of

227
00:13:29.028 --> 00:13:31.268
new neoantigens for the immune system to see.

228
00:13:31.358 --> 00:13:34.948
So taking the brakes off that, then we can see responses.

229
00:13:35.288 --> 00:13:38.928
But as you can tell, there are many tumors over here

230
00:13:39.228 --> 00:13:43.068
that really don't have enough neoantigens and are poor responders,

231
00:13:43.148 --> 00:13:46.648
we know from the clinic, to single-agent checkpoint therapies.

232
00:13:46.678 --> 00:13:50.288
And we're talking about KRAS here, so I'll highlight where the pancreatic

233
00:13:50.668 --> 00:13:52.028
tumors lie. Very

234
00:13:53.488 --> 00:13:57.248
little of those high tumor mutations in most

235
00:13:57.288 --> 00:14:01.228
tumors. So with these kinds of tumors, where we are in

236
00:14:01.248 --> 00:14:04.848
the RAS field, how do we get more responses?

237
00:14:05.308 --> 00:14:09.168
And I think one of the really nice examples that

238
00:14:09.208 --> 00:14:13.048
emerged in the last few years from the Sloan Kettering group

239
00:14:13.168 --> 00:14:16.368
and Roche Genentech group was to develop

240
00:14:16.428 --> 00:14:19.808
personalized neoantigen mRNA vaccines

241
00:14:20.628 --> 00:14:22.888
in early pancreatic cancer patients,

242
00:14:23.868 --> 00:14:27.808
pair that with checkpoint therapy and standard of care chemotherapy,

243
00:14:28.248 --> 00:14:32.208
post-surgical resection. And I wanted to take you

244
00:14:32.268 --> 00:14:34.948
through that because I think it's a very

245
00:14:36.608 --> 00:14:40.108
promising strategy, although you'll see it is

246
00:14:40.208 --> 00:14:43.288
highly labor and computational and

247
00:14:43.488 --> 00:14:46.468
it's a personalized

248
